                                        <h5 tabindex="0" class="card-title text-center text-md-start mb-2">Choosing Conversation Topics</h5>
                                        <p tabindex="0" class="card-text">When discussing social skills with my students, the ability to choose appropriate conversation topics is a common area they want to improve. I explain that a good topic should meet three criteria: it should be interesting to all participants, have common ground so everyone can contribute, and be appropriate for everyone involved. However, there are exceptions to these guidelines. For instance, storytelling or sharing information may not require common ground. Similarly, topics considered inappropriate, such as sex, politics, or religion, can be discussed with specific individuals like close family members, friends, or counselors. To facilitate this skill, I provide a checklist handout. During group sessions, we individually fill out the handout, marking topics as interesting, familiar, and appropriate for our specific group.</p>
